fields.description:
Allow selecting to add columns *Satisfaction Comment* and •Satisfaction Date* to the JQL results.

The business need is that I can run JQL:
{code:java}
project = pvs and Satisfaction is not EMPTY and "Satisfaction Comment" ~ great and "Satisfaction date" >= 2020-01-01
{code}
and then I can add all 3 columns to the results set view in Jira.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-28290].
  {panel}

{panel:title=Atlassian Status as of 13 August 2014|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#3C78B5| titleBGColor=#3C78B5| bgColor=#E7F4FA}
Hi All,

Thanks so much for your votes and comments on this feature request.

After analysis of this issue we decided it is not something we can put on our short to mid term roadmap. Therefore we think it is only fair to not keep this issue as open and close it as "won't fix". We will take this feedback into account as we work on ongoing design and usability improvements to the view issue page.


Cheers,
Jason
JIRA Product Management
jwong (at) atlassian (dot) com
{panel}

*Original description*
When using JIRA, I often change the attachment sort order. I would really like to have a 'default sort order' so I don't have to do it as often.

h3. Workaround:

This is an unsupported, and hacky workaround but hopefully it helps some people. You can use the following code in your announcement banner:
{code}<script>var direction = "asc"; //Other option is "desc"
var sortBy = "dateTime"; //Other option is "fileName"

var origUrl = window.location.href;
var patt = /browse\/[A-Z][A-Z]+-[0-9]+/;
var key = new RegExp("[A-Z][A-Z]+-[0-9]+");

var sort = "?attachmentSortBy="+sortBy+"&attachmentOrder="+direction+"#attachmentmodule";
if(patt.test(origUrl) && !JSON.parse(sessionStorage.getItem('hasReloaded' + key))){
	location.assign(origUrl + sort);
	sessionStorage.setItem('hasReloaded' + key, 'true');
} else {
    sessionStorage.setItem('hasReloaded' + key, 'false');
}</script>{code}

This will automatically switch to sorting by Date Ascending. You can tweak it to suit your needs. 
(i) *This will only work for JIRA server installations. JIRA Cloud [does not support|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRA-27864] inserting custom code into the announcement banner.*

If you are on cloud, or are an individual user that wants to have this functionality without inserting it for everyone, you can use the user script: [^JIRA Order Attachments by Date.user.js] within [Tampermonkey|https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/tampermonkey/dhdgffkkebhmkfjojejmpbldmpobfkfo?hl=en] for Chrome, or [Greasemonkey|https://addons.mozilla.org/en-us/firefox/addon/greasemonkey/] for Firefox.

h3. Issue Summary

When editing a comment that starts with an Emoji under the new issue view rich text editor results in cursor misbehaving (either through arrow keys or with mouse direct placement). The cursor placement is misleading and makes it difficult adding content when editing a comment.

Can be replicated in Chrome whereas in Safari the problem does not occur.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Under the new issue view using Rich text editor add a comment that starts with an emoji;
 # Save it;
 # Press _Edit;_
 # Place the I-beam pointer anywhere in the text section;

h3. Expected Results

We should be able to precisely place the I-beam pointer anywhere and expect additional content to appear in that location accordingly;
h3. Actual Results

When placing the I-beam pointer in between any character it is not possible to predict where additional text will be added;
** !example.gif|thumbnail!
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Summary

Allow Automation to get the value of field type "Domain of Reporter"
h3. How to reproduce
 # Create a field with the type "*Domain of Reporter*"
 # Create an issue.
 # Try to get the "*Domain of Reporter*" field value from this issue.
{code:java}
{{issue.customfield_10317}} 
{code}
{code:java}
{{issue.customfield_10317.value}}
{code}

 * [Image|https://share.getcloudapp.com/Qwu9vlQY] with a field filled out with a domain.
 * [Image|https://share.getcloudapp.com/6quQm2L1] from an automation rule that was not able to get this value.

h3. Workaround

We'll be able to get the reporter domain using this smart value below:
{code:java}
{{reporter.emailAddress.split("@").last}}
{code}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSWSERVER-20097].
  {panel}

It could be useful to be able to search for issues that were added or removed from a sprint during it's progress.

A customer even tried to get help from Script Runner support, but the according to the support, the respective function that could return that result is available only to the Server version of Script Runner.

It would be great to have it built natively.
